gument, this syntax is much less common.\n","\n","Like all Python arguments, there is no need for `self` to be named `self`, we could also call it `this` or `apple` or `wizard`. However, the use of `self` is a very strong Python convention which is rarely broken. You should use this convention so that your code is understood by other people."],"metadata":{"id":"_FrlHqCTDwL1"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["<font size=\"+1\">Practice</font>\n","\n","Define a `Square` object with only one attribute: `side`."],"metadata":{"id":"AswNsAOPENxx"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class Square(object):\n","    \n","​\n","​\n","Square"],"metadata":{"id":"wZxVw-v-EQCv"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Define a method on its area for the `Square` object:"],"metadata":{"id":"ymsNuOiSERuM"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class Square(object):\n","    \n","Square"],"metadata":{"id":"aSfqVTKAEaZZ"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Use the class you just defined to calculate the area of a square with side equals to 2."],"metadata":{"id":"ukghNs4OEcZS"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["square = ..."],"metadata":{"id":"QJytyclCEd2k"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **3. Inheritance**\n","\n","Inheritance means we can define a class that inherits everything from another existing class, including its `method` and `attributes`. Inheritance enables us to create new classes that reuse, extend, and modify the behavior defined in other classes. For example, let's use the `Rectangle` class as an example:"],"metadata":{"id":"A8__PO5qElOB"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class Rectangle(object):\n","    def __init__(self, height, length):\n","        self.height = height\n","        self.length = length\n","​\n","    def area(self):\n","        return self.height * self.length\n","​\n","    def perimeter(self):\n","        return 2 * (self.height + self.length)"],"metada